I believe that utilizing a static query might not be the best fit for your current scenario. Instead, I recommend leveraging the `CriteriaAPI`, a flexible approach in Hibernate/JPA for crafting dynamic queries.

Let&#39;s assume you intend to search for `User` entities using this approach:

```java
List&lt;FilterCondition&gt; and = List.of(
    new FilterCondition(&quot;id&quot;, &quot;in&quot;, List.of(1, 2, 3)),
    new FilterCondition(&quot;name&quot;, &quot;eq&quot;, &quot;example name&quot;));

Filter filter = new Filter(and);

CriteriaBuilder criteriaBuilder = entityManager.getCriteriaBuilder();
CriteriaQuery&lt;User&gt; criteriaQuery = criteriaBuilder.createQuery(User.class);
Root&lt;User&gt; root = criteriaQuery.from(User.class);

List&lt;Predicate&gt; predicates = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

for (FilterCondition condition : filter.getAnd()) {
    String fieldName = condition.getField();
    Path&lt;?&gt; path = root.get(fieldName);
    
    if (&quot;in&quot;.equals(condition.getOperator())) {
        List&lt;?&gt; values = (List&lt;?&gt;) condition.getValue();
        predicates.add(path.in(values));
    } else if (&quot;eq&quot;.equals(condition.getOperator())) {
        Object value = condition.getValue();
        predicates.add(criteriaBuilder.equal(path, value));
    }
}

criteriaQuery.where(criteriaBuilder.and(predicates.toArray(new Predicate[0])));
List&lt;User&gt; users = em.createQuery(criteriaQuery).getResultList();
```

This approach is especially useful for building complex queries based on various filter conditions.

